According to director Kelsey Mann, the new character promises to stir things up within headquarters. â€œAnxiety, voiced by Maya Hawke, might be new to the crew, but sheâ€™s not really the type to take a back seat,â€ said Mann. â€œThat makes a lot of sense if you think about it in terms of what goes on inside all our minds.â€ A trailer, poster and film stills are now available for what promises to be the feel-good (or feel-everything) film of Summer 2024. Disney and Pixarâ€™s â€œInside Out 2â€ returns to the mind of newly minted teenager Riley just as headquarters is undergoing a sudden demolition to make room for something entirely unexpected: new Emotions! Joy, Sadness, Anger, Fear and Disgust, whoâ€™ve long been running a successful operation by all accounts, arenâ€™t sure how to feel when Anxiety shows up. And it looks like sheâ€™s not alone. Maya Hawke lends her voice to Anxiety, alongside Amy Poehler as Joy, Phyllis Smith as Sadness, Lewis Black as Anger, Tony Hale as Fear, and Liza Lapira as Disgust. Directed by Kelsey Mann and produced by Mark Nielsen, â€œInside Out 2â€ releases only in theaters Summer 2024.

title: Something weird happens when you keep squeezing
tags: CMAP|Vox.com|atomic pressure|earth|earth's core|explain|explainer|hydraulic press|molecules|physics|pressure|science|vox|center for atomic pressure|adam cole|adam cole npr|sodium|hydrogen|solar system|lasers|temperatures|stars|nuclear|nuclear fusion|atoms|helium
description: Under extreme pressures, matter defies the rules of physics as we know it.Help keep Vox free for everybody: http://www.vox.com/give-now Subscribe to our channel and turn on notifications (ğŸ””) so you don't miss any videos: http://goo.gl/0bsAjOPhysicists have a pretty good handle on how stuff behaves on the surface of the Earth. But a lot of matter in the universe exists outside this narrow band of relatively low temperatures and pressures. Inside planets and stars, the crushing force of gravity begins to overwhelm the electromagnetic and nuclear forces that keep atoms apart and maintain the shapes of molecules. What happens next? Scientists (including a consortia of researchers at the NSFâ€™s Center for Matter at Atomic Pressuresâ€‹â€‹) are just starting to figure that out. They use a variety of tools (including some humongous lasers) to simulate planetary cores and see what happens. A few standout findings so far:Water can become a hot black ice that conducts electricity: https://www.quantamagazine.org/black-hot-superionic-ice-may-be-natures-most-common-form-of-water-20190508/Hydrogen gas can be compressed down into a shiny metal: https://www.newscientist.com/article/2119442-metallic-hydrogen-finally-made-in-lab-at-mind-boggling-pressure/Sodium (a soft, silvery metal at atmospheric pressure) can turn transparent: https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/03/090312180838.htmPresented by the Center for Matter at Atomic Pressures (CMAP) at the University of Rochester,a National Science Foundation (NSF) Physics Frontier Center, Award PHY-2020249 https://cmap.rochester.edu/What happens under extreme pressures deep with planets also influences their ability to foster life. Check out our videos about the search for Earth-like worlds beyond our solar system:What we found when we went looking for another Earth: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lrAFaONyLtUHow to find a planet you canâ€™t see:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=STsI6IbPbGQ Hereâ€™s  a closer look at another giant laser (at the National Ignition Facility):https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gMaKhXkihGQ To see a classic film that takes a similar approach to understanding distances (from the microscopic to the galactic) check out â€œPowers of Tenâ€:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0fKBhvDjuy0 This material is based upon work of the Center for Matter at Atomic Pressures (CMAP), supported by the National Science Foundation under Grant No. PHY-2020249. title: I Was Trafficked Through The World's Deadliest Jungle
tags: DARIEN|Darien jungle|migrants|venezuela|snake pass|elon musk|bald and bankrupt|Timmy karter|south america|adventure|travel|journalism|documentary
description: The Darien Gap known as the world's most dangerous jungle. I had heard of the Darien many years ago through National Geographic and it had both fascinated and intimidated me. I knew one day I would have to visit...When the word Darien started appearing in the news in recent years by way of the migrant crises I decided that now was the time to explore it for myself. And so myself and my good friend @TimmyKarter headed north from Medellin in search of a way across the infamous jungle, avoiding cartel and bandits, injury and tropical diseases, on an adventure with migrants from all over the world where national laws don't apply. Only the laws of the jungle.Join us as we enter...the Darien.

description: Starlink is SpaceXâ€™s answer to providing global, high-speed internet coverage using a network of thousands of satellites buzzing around the planet in a region known as low Earth orbit (LEO), about 342 miles above the Earthâ€™s surface. SpaceX launched its first batch of Starlink satellites back in 2019, and since then, adoption of the service has ballooned. Starlink now has over 2 million active customers and is available on all 7 continents and in over 60 countries. Starlink has been praised for its ability to connect remote parts of the world that would otherwise not have access to reliable internet. The service has also become indispensable in areas hit by natural disasters, and, more recently, during times of war, particularly the Russia-Ukraine war. But Starlinkâ€™s growing influence is garnering condemnation from some who say that SpaceX CEO, Elon Musk is meddling in geopolitics, while the scientific community is raising alarms of the effect of thousands of satellites on radio and optical astronomy.Chapters:00:00 - 03:03 Intro03:03 - 06:36 Behind Starlinkâ€™s growth06:36 - 10:33 Starlink and geopolitics10:33 - 15:35 Scientific concerns15:35 - 18:38 FutureProduced and Edited by: Magdalena PetrovaAnimation: Mallory BranganSupervising Producer: Jeniece PettittEditorial Support: Michael SheetzAdditional Footage: Getty ImagesÂ» Subscribe to CNBC: https://cnb.cx/SubscribeCNBCÂ» Subscribe to CNBC TV: https://cnb.cx/SubscribeCNBCtelevisionAbout CNBC: From 'Wall Street' to 'Main Street' to award winning original documentaries and Reality TV series, CNBC has you covered. description: Now and Then's eventful journey to fruition took place over five decades and is the product of conversations and collaborations between the four Beatles that go on to this day. The long mythologised John Lennon demo was first worked on in February 1995 by Paul, George and Ringo as part of The Beatles Anthology project but it remained unfinished, partly because of the impossible technological challenges involved in working with the vocal John had recorded on tape in the 1970s. For years it looked like the song could never be completed. But in 2022 there was a stroke of serendipity. A software system developed by Peter Jackson and his team, used throughout the production of the documentary series Get Back, finally opened the way for the uncoupling of Johnâ€™s vocal from his piano part. As a result, the original recording could be brought to life and worked on anew with contributions from all four Beatles. This remarkable story of musical archaeology reflects The Beatlesâ€™ endless creative curiosity and shared fascination with technology. It marks the completion of the last recording that John, Paul and George and Ringo will get to make together and celebrates the legacy of the foremost and most influential band in popular music history.Video Director: Peter JacksonVideo Producers: Peter Jackson, Clare Olssen, Jonathan ClydeAudio Producers: Paul McCartney and Giles MartinProduction Company: WingNut Films Productions LtdOrder/Listen to Now And Then: https://TheBeatles.lnk.to/NowAndThenYTOrder/Listen to Red and Blue: https://TheBeatles.lnk.to/RedAndBlue2023YTWatch more videos from The Beatles: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/YTPlaylists Subscribe to The Beatlesâ€™ YouTube channel & ring the bell to never miss a new video: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/YTSignup Sign up for The Beatlesâ€™ Official Email List: https://www.thebeatles.com/newsletter   Stream The Beatles: ğŸ™ï¸ Apple Music: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/stream/AppleMusic ğŸ™ï¸ Spotify: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/stream/Spotify ğŸ™ï¸ Amazon Music: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/stream/AmazonMusic ğŸ™ï¸ Pandora: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/stream/Pandora ğŸ™ï¸ Tidal: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/stream/Tidal ğŸ™ï¸ Deezer: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/stream/Deezer ğŸ™ï¸ YouTube Music: https://thebeatles.lnk.to/stream/YouTubeMusic   Follow The Beatles:  â­ https://www.thebeatles.com â­ https://www.instagram.com/thebeatlesâ­ https://www.facebook.com/thebeatlesâ­ https://www.tiktok.com/@thebeatlesâ­ https://twitter.com/thebeatles #TheBeatles #NowAndThen #JohnLennon #PaulMcCartney #GeorgeHarrison #RingoStarr

Before I was a mother and a wife I felt such a sense of purpose and passion pouring all of my time into work.Now in 2023, a lot has changed. Priorities have shifted, business goals have been refined and most importantly, I have become a wife and a mother. This season of motherhood has been my greatest blessing and an experience I know is fleeting. In our life there is time to do everything, but not all at once. With all of this in mind and my intentions to create more balance in my life, I have come to the decision to close down the Sunee App. When I work on a project or product, I will give it my all and nothing less. Considering all avenues and possibilities for the app's future, the decision to close the app has been one that has given me the greatest sense of peace.In saying this, this has not been a decision I have made lightly as I know how special and impactful Sunee and our recipes are to so many of you. I want to take this moment to sincerely thank every single one of you who have supported Sunee. None of this would have been possible without you and Iâ€™m so grateful that you have been along for this amazing journey!While the app will no longer exist, this is not goodbye. My passion for creating healthy recipes is deeper than ever, however, my approach and pace will now honour my season. The experience of creating my cookbook was the confirmation I needed to acknowledge that right now in my life, I need to be working on a project basis.. This allows me to pour all of my creativity into my work, whilst prioritising my role as a mother and raising my boys.Again, thank you all for your support and love.For more details on the closure of the Sunee app head to www.sunee.com/closing
